    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait what do you mean by goblin note? i was just asking about the math. anyway, can you explain how the salvage value affects the calculation again? i'm a bit confused on that part.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the **Salvage Value** is the \"ghost\" that keeps the goblins from eating your entire fortune! You see, the formula is:\n\n**Depreciation Expense = (Cost of Asset - Salvage Value) / Useful Life**\n\nThink of it this way: The **Cost** is the goblin's full stash of gold coins. The **Salvage Value** is the tiny, unloved scrap of gold left over when the goblins finally decide to stop playing and just sit there.\n\nIf the Salvage Value is zero, the goblins take *everything* (Cost). If the Salvage Value is high, the goblins only take the difference between what they started with and what they left behind.\n\nIn your example:\n*   **Cost:** $50,000 (The full goblin stash).\n*   **Salvage Value:** $5,000 (The little scrap left over).\n*   **Net Value for Depreciation:** $50,000 - $5,000 = $45,000.\n\nSo, the goblins only get to eat $45,000",
      "source": "target",
